w, and the freedom of the press-it is not clear that these difficulties threaten political legitimacy. Such ambiguity derives in part from the contested nature of the concept of legitimacy, and from disagreements over how to measure it. This volume reflects the cutting edge of responses to these perennial questions, drawing, in the distinctive NOMOS fashion, from political science, philosophy, and law. Contributors address fundamental philosophical questions such as the nature of public reasons of authority, as well as urgent concerns about contemporary democracy, including whether "animus" matters for the legitimacy of President Trump's travel ban, barring entry for nationals from six Muslim-majority nations, and the effect of fundamental transitions within the moral economy, such as the decline of labor unions. Featuring twelve essays from leading scholars, Political Legitimacy is an important and timely addition to the NOMOS series.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aAuthority. 0aLegitimacy of governments. 0aSovereignty. 4aAristotle. 4aKant. 4aNGOs. 4aStilz. 4aauthority. 4acoercion. 4acolonialism. 4acompliance. 4aconsent. 4acooperation. 4afreedom. 4aintention. 4ajustification. 4alegal authority. 4amoral economy. 4anon-state actors. 4aobedience. 4apermissibility. 4apolitical autonomy. 4apolitical epistemology. 4apolitical obligation. 4aprocedural justice. 4apublic reason. 4arepublicanism. 4aresistance. 4aright to err. 4aself-determination. 4asovereignty. 4astability. 4atravel ban. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aKnight, Jack, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchwartzberg, Melissa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479869206423Coveruhttps://ww